  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The primary purpose of money laundering is to obscure the origin of the funds, making it difficult for authorities to trace them back to criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or tax evasion.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited by law. The country has established a comprehensive legal framework to combat money laundering, including the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China** and related regulations. The government actively cooperates with international organizations and other countries to combat financial crimes and ensure the integrity of the financial system.\n\nThe Chinese government emphasizes the importance of maintaining financial security and social stability, and it encourages all citizens and institutions to abide by the law and report any suspicious activities related to money laundering.",
